{{AncientRome-myth-stub}}

The total primary energy consumption of the [[Philippines]] in 2012 was 30.2 Mtoe (million [[Tonne of oil equivalent|Tonnes of oil equivalent]]),<ref name=bp2013>{{cite book|title=Statistical Review of World Energy 2013|year=2013|publisher=BP|url=http://www.bp.com/content/dam/bp/pdf/statistical-review/statistical_review_of_world_energy_2013.pdf|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130814004347/http://www.bp.com/content/dam/bp/pdf/statistical-review/statistical_review_of_world_energy_2013.pdf|archivedate=2013-08-14|df=}}</ref> most of which came from fossil fuels. Electricity consumption in 2010 was 64.52 TWh, of which almost two-thirds came from fossil fuels, 21% from [[Hydroelectricity|hydroelectric plants]], and 13% from other renewable sources. The total generating capacity was 16.36 GW.<ref name=ciawf>{{cite web|title=Philippines |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/rp.html |work=World Factbook |publisher=CIA - Central Intelligence Agency |accessdate=16 August 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100111070218/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/rp.html |archivedate=11 January 2010 |df= }}</ref>
The population of the Philippines is over 101 million people,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldometers.info/world-population/philippines-population/|title=Philippines Population (2016) - Worldometers|website=www.worldometers.info|access-date=2016-04-08}}</ref> and as a rapidly developing nation, has seen a rapid increase in GDP, averaging 6.1% from 2011 to 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NY.GDP.MKTP.KD.ZG|title=GDP growth (annual %) {{!}} Data {{!}} Table|website=data.worldbank.org|access-date=2016-04-08}}</ref> Energy-intensive manufacturing and retail industries are the driving factors of the Philippines' economic growth.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=April 2015|title=Economy, Finance and Trade: Philippines|url=|journal=Euromonitor|doi=|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref> Given its large population and rapidly growing economy, the country's energy needs are significant and growing rapidly. According to the Philippines [[Department of Energy (Philippines)|Department of Energy]], the Philippines consumed 75,266 gigawatt-hours (GWh) of electricity in 2013.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |url=http://www.doe.gov.ph/electric-power-statistics/philippine-power-statistics/2498-2013-philippine-power-statistics |title=2013 Philippine Power Statistics |last=Membrere |first=Leah N. |website=www.doe.gov.ph |access-date=2016-04-08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160410230734/http://www.doe.gov.ph/electric-power-statistics/philippine-power-statistics/2498-2013-philippine-power-statistics |archivedate=2016-04-10 |df= }}</ref> Of this, 27.39% went to powering residential areas, 24.31% to commercial establishments and 27.46% to the industrial sector. With 72.84% of electrical energy being consumed by [[Luzon]], 14.75% by Visayas, and 12.41% by Mindanao in 2013.
==Electricity== {{main article|Electricity sector in the Philippines}}
{{Pie chart |caption=Percentage of electricity used by major islands |label1=Luzon |value1=72.84 |color1=Purple |label2=Visayas |value2=14.75 |color2=Orange |label3=Mindanao |value3=12.41 |color3=Green}} {{Pie chart |caption=Percentage of electricity used by different sectors |label1=Commercial |value1=24.31 |color1=Purple |label2=Industrial |value2=27.46 |color2=Green |label3=Residential |value3=27.39 |color3=Orange |label4=Other |value4=20.84 |color4=Red}}
The Philippines’ demand for electrical energy in 2013 represents a 42.17% increase from 2012{{fact|date=May 2017}}, when the demand for energy was at 52,941 GWh.<ref name=":0" /> It is expected that the country’s demand for power will increase as the Philippines’ population and economy continue to grow.
The Philippines’ current energy mix highly favors fossil fuels, with [[coal]], [[natural gas]], and [[oil]], accounting for 73.56% of the country's total electrical energy needs,<ref name=":0" /> primarily due to their low cost.<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|title=World energy Perspective: Cost of energy Technologies|last=|first=|publisher=World energy Council|year=2013|isbn=978 0 94612 130 4|location=|pages=4–41}}</ref>
The Philippines's most heavily used energy source is coal.<ref name=":0" /> Of the country’s 75,266 GWh electrical energy demand in 2013, 32,081 GWh or approximately 42.62% was sourced from coal. This heavy dependence on coal is further apparent by the high number of coal-fired power plants in the country. As of March 2016, there were 32 coal-fired power generation facilities connected to the energy grid.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web |url=http://www.doe.gov.ph/doe_files/pdf/01_Energy_Situationer/2015_existing_power_plants_luzon_december_2015.pdf |title=List of Existing Plants (Luzon) |last= |first= |date=2016 |website=Department of Energy |publisher=Department of Energy |access-date= |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418192407/http://www.doe.gov.ph/doe_files/pdf/01_Energy_Situationer/2015_existing_power_plants_luzon_december_2015.pdf |archivedate=2016-04-18 |df= }}</ref><ref name=":3">{{Cite web|url=http://www.doe.gov.ph/doe_files/pdf/01_Energy_Situationer/2015_existing_power_plants_visayas_december_2015.pdf |title=List of Existing Plants (Visayas) |last= |first= |date= |website=Department of Energy |publisher=Department of Energy |access-date= |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610233915/http://www.doe.gov.ph/doe_files/pdf/01_energy_Situationer/2015_existing_power_plants_visayas_december_2015.pdf |archivedate=2016-06-10 |df= }}</ref><ref name=":4">{{Cite web|url=http://www.doe.gov.ph/doe_files/pdf/01_Energy_Situationer/2015_existing_power_plants_mindanao_december_2015.pdf |title=List of Existing Plants (Mindanao) |last= |first= |date= |website=Department of Energy |publisher=Department of Energy |access-date= |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610235053/http://www.doe.gov.ph/doe_files/pdf/01_energy_Situationer/2015_existing_power_plants_mindanao_december_2015.pdf |archivedate=2016-06-10 |df= }}</ref> These facilities are spread throughout the country, although most of them are in Luzon and Visayas. The number of coal-fired power plants in the country is set to increase by 25 by the year 2030 to keep up with the Philippines’ growing energy demands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/773681/why-is-ph-building-25-more-coal-powered-plants|title=Why is PH building 25 more coal-powered plants?|last=Quismundo|first=Tarra|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|access-date=2016-04-08}}</ref>
Besides coal, the Philippines is also heavily dependent on natural gas{{fact|date=May 2017}}. The Philippines produced 18,791 GWh of electricity from natural gas in 2013.<ref name=":0" /> This corresponded to 24.97% of the Philippines’ electrical energy needs during this period. As of March 2016, there were a total of 13 natural gas generation facilities connected to the energy grid,<ref name=":2" /><ref name=":3" /><ref name=":4" /> 12 of which are in [[Luzon]] and one of which is in [[Cebu]] on Visayas.
The Philippines also generates a significant amount of electrical energy from oil, albeit to a lesser degree than compared to coal and natural gas. In 2013, the Philippines sourced 5.97% of its energy from oil-based sources.<ref name=":0" /> As of March 2016, there were a total of 212 gas and [[Diesel fuel|diesel]]-powered facilities in the Philippines.<ref name=":2" /><ref name=":3" /><ref name=":4" /> The large number of oil-powered power plants is a result of a lower per plant output compared to coal and natural gas. Oil-powered power plants can be found dispersed across several provinces in Luzon, [[Visayas]], and [[Mindanao]].
== Renewable energy == The Government of the Philippines has introduced various policies to foster renewable energy. Some of the policies provide an income tax holiday up to seven years, duty-free import of equipment for renewable energy technologies, etc. In 2012, the government launched the new feed-in tariff (FIT).{{Explain|date=May 2017}}
